---
import BlogPostLayout from "../../layouts/BlogPostLayout.astro";

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are the signs of a dirty chimney?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The main signs of a dirty chimney are: smoke coming back into the room when the fire is lit; a persistent smoky or burnt smell even when the fire is off; fires that are slow to start or hard to keep going; heavily blackened glass on your wood heater door; visible soot or debris falling into the firebox; a dark oily staining around the fireplace opening; and reduced draw or a sluggish, struggling fire. Any of these signs means your chimney needs sweeping."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I know if my chimney needs cleaning?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The clearest signs your chimney needs cleaning are smoke spilling back into the room, a smoky smell when the fire isn't burning, glass that goes black quickly, fires that struggle to draw, and visible soot or debris in the firebox. If you can't remember when it was last cleaned — or if it's been more than a year — it needs doing regardless of whether you've noticed any symptoms."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can a dirty chimney make you sick?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. A blocked or heavily sooted flue can force carbon monoxide and other combustion gases back into your living space. Carbon monoxide is colourless, odourless and potentially fatal. Symptoms of CO exposure include headache, nausea, dizziness and fatigue — often mistaken for a cold or flu. If you suspect CO is entering your home from a fireplace or wood heater, ventilate immediately and don't use the appliance until the flue has been inspected."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does creosote look like in a chimney?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Creosote appears in three stages: Stage 1 is a light, flaky grey or black soot that brushes off easily. Stage 2 is a harder, tar-like black crust that sticks to the flue liner. Stage 3 is a shiny, glassy black coating that is extremely hard, difficult to remove, and highly flammable. Most homeowners will see evidence of Stage 1 or 2 as black deposits around the firebox opening or on the glass — Stage 3 requires professional removal."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why does my fireplace smell even when it's not on?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A smoky or burnt smell from a fireplace when it's not in use is almost always caused by creosote or old ash deposits in the flue. The smell intensifies in humid weather or when air pressure draws air down the chimney rather than up. It's a clear sign the chimney needs sweeping. In older homes it can also indicate a cracked flue liner allowing flue gases to seep into wall cavities."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why does my wood heater glass go black?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Wood heater glass goes black from incomplete combustion — unburnt particles deposit on the glass instead of going up the flue. The most common causes are burning wet or unseasoned wood, running the fire too low or damped down, or a restricted flue that isn't drawing properly. A dirty, sooted-up flue reduces airflow and directly causes glass blackening. A clean flue and dry hardwood should keep the glass relatively clear."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is a little soot in the fireplace normal?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A small amount of fine grey ash in the firebox is normal. However, thick black soot deposits, oily black residue around the fireplace opening, or soot falling from inside the flue are not normal and indicate a dirty or restricted chimney that needs cleaning. Any black staining on the ceiling or walls near the fireplace is a serious sign of smoke spillage and requires immediate attention."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens if you don't clean a dirty chimney?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "An uncleaned chimney progressively restricts airflow, reducing heating efficiency and increasing smoke spillage. More seriously, creosote buildup is the primary cause of chimney fires — which can reach over 1,000°C and cause structural damage or house fires. A blocked flue also creates carbon monoxide risk. Insurance policies for properties with wood heaters typically require annual maintenance, so an uncleaned chimney can affect your ability to make a claim."
      }
    }
  ]
};
